"Abstract With increasing reliance being placed on the use of computer technology by every sector of society, computer-based evidence is becoming a bigger and bigger issue daily. The task facing the legal profession or the investigator when it comes to uncovering and interpreting potential evidence is markedly different today than, say, just six to 10 years ago. Instead of wading through mountains of paper it is more common to meet evidence held in electronic format on one or more computers. The technology revolution has also generated new avenues for crime, requiring a great deal of technical awareness and computer literacy from everyone involved. Clifford May looks at the special problems involved in the identification and recovery of computer-based evidence in a form that can be successfully presented to court."
